These best practices reflect recommendations shared by a cross-functional team of seasoned Lookers. These insights come from years of experience working with Looker customers from implementation to long-term success.
A defined process exists for end-users to make modeling requests.
Not sure if you have a process for this, but it's an important one! Here are some ideas:
- #Messaging-channel: Create a Looker messaging channel (like Slack or Hipchat) so that all users can ask quick questions, make requests and share wins
- Email alias: Make a Looker specific email alias to send requests
- Office hours: Hold bi-weekly office hours with specific topics or just for general questions
- Newsletter: Communicate new content and notable Looker releases in a monthly Looker newsletter
Whatever your process, post it directly in Looker on the homepage sidebar! https://docs.looker.com/admin-options/tutorials/notify-users
A defined process exists to organize and prioritize modeling requests.
A defined process exists to communicate with end-users about their requests.
Code reviews of pull requests ensure compliance with standards.
PRs are not required. This is not necessary, but would be a good way to enforce the standards are being followed.
Periodic audits of existing code ensures compliance with standards.
Henry (or similar) is used to monitor and manage LookML model complexity.
as your model grows over time, it is good to occasionally run Henry to scrape it for unused tables, explores, and fields to spot technical debt and reduce model bloat.
LookML and SQL style guides formalize acceptable patterns and conventions.
Your style guide does not need to be as thought out as this "LAMS" example guide, but it is good to have some sort of development guidelines. For example, you might write a guide that says:
- make all LookML file names lowercase, since they are case sensitive
- always put an owner at the top of a derived table, so people know who the owner is, and can direct their questions there
- every table should have a primary key

You can post this guide in a document file in the LookML, so all developers can see it directly where they work: https://docs.looker.com/data-modeling/getting-started/other-project-files#document_files
When referencing date fields inside of other LookML fields, reference “raw” to avoid date-conversion performance degradation.
Code minimizes repetition with the use of inheritance features like extends and project import. Supplemental comments in the code make these building blocks easy to understand.
are used to create a catalogue of accessible, repeatable text that reduces repetition throughout the LookML. Constants can be used for HTML snippets, labels, connection names, table names, and more.
LookML fields are defined and reused with the ${substitution} operator instead of redundant ${TABLE}.column references
Sometimes, but not always. The value of using ${substitution} is that it enforces code reusability.
For example, in this file you have two measures that reference ${TABLE}.events: events_last_year, and events_prev_period.

Instead, you should have a dimension that references the raw thing (${TABLE}.events), then reference ${events} in the two measures. This way, if you ever want to make a change to ${events}, you would only need to make this change in one place (on the dimension), and it will cascade to both measures.
File-naming conventions and #comment headers describe the contents of files.
Put a #comment header at the top of each view file that says what the file contains, ESPECIALLY important for derived tables (since those are harder to understand to fresh eyes what they are doing)
organize LookML files. Individual files of a similar theme no longer need uniform name pre-fixes to group them in an include statement. Rather, nest them in an IDE folder and include the folder.

These will be a huge improvement to the readability and organization to the LookML code. Instead of scrolling through so many files, developers can work within a single folder at a time with all the related files they need at once. I suggest making a different folder for widely different types of data/ use cases. So you might have one for news_sites, and another for education. Within those folders, you can make subfolders for views and models. In the model file, you can include only the directories with the relevant files. So for example, in the education folder, you'd have a model in the model sub-folder, and it would reference all views in the views sub-folder like this:
Warning: when you first implement this change, you are going to have a ton of temporary LookML errors, and it is going to be VERY scary for you. To make this easier:
1. Make sure all other changes in your current branch are committed.
2. Create a new branch called "creating_folders" for this new work so that it is separate, and you can abandon it / put it aside if you need to get back to different work in your personal branch.
3. Make the changes! Be brave! It will be worth it!
to include everything in a folder, including everything in sub-folders in that folder, you can say:
The two stars grab everything, regardless of subfolder.
No fields that generate errors or broken content can be found.
A popular explore generates an error from a date field:
Old or deprecated LookML code should be deleted or placed in separate files rather than merely commented out.
Lots of code should be cleaned up of commented out code. For example, this file: https://haymarket.looker.com/projects/haymarket/files/ga_universe.view.lkml?line=1
A development and staging workflow is used to promote changes.
Distribute PDT refresh times to off-peak hours and to not affect users.

A view declaration defines a list of fields (dimensions or measures) and their linkage to an underlying table or derived table. In LookML a view typically references an underlying database table, but it can also represent a derived table.
Fields unnecessary for analytics (often created by auto-generation of view files) are deleted. Fields that are important to analytics but that end users don't need to see (like primary keys) are
parameters are used to make field picker intuitive.
Boolean dimensions are named with questions rather than statements, for example, "is_returned" versus "returned?"
Sometimes! And sometimes not. This is another example of something that would be good to document in your style guide!
Ratio measures should be named so that the division operation is clearly understood. For example, “Orders Per Purchasing Customers” is clearer than “Orders Percent.”
To increase the readability of number values, use the following:
for pre-configured out of the box formats, and
to make your excel-style formatting reusable.
in model files, explores, and derived tables when persistence is required. Haphazard usage of persist_for as a caching strategy is minimized.
datagroups are defined, but it's unclear if they are being used?
Ensure that all Views and Derived Tables have primary keys defined.
Use of set definition for drill_fields and fields parameters. set attributes are easier to manage as compared to hidden attribute to show/hide fields in explores.
Some, but not all, measures have drill fields

An Explore is a view that users can query. You can think of the Explore as a starting point for a query, or in SQL terms, as the FROM in a SQL statement. Not all views are Explores, because not all views describe an entity of interest.
are used to define the purpose of each explore.

Every explore should have a description to say what data is in it. This is really important when you let non-technical users loose in the instance. Otherwise, they won't know which explore to use and will be confused! Descriptions are especially important for explores with similar tables (tell the user when they would use one instead of the other. If you don't know the answer, you should delete one!)

Avoid indirect/fannout type relationships between granular tables.  In other words, avoid many_to_many relationships, and one_to_many relationships.(*exception for one_to_many: the one most granular table, if not always used, may not be a desirable base table and may be an appropriate as the only one_to_many join in the explore).
Use the fewest number of Explores that allows users to easily answer the questions they have on a subject. Consider splitting the Explores in separate models based on audience and use cases.
What is the difference between "Match Rate", "Match Rate Adv", and "Match Rate Testing"?
Limit the number of views joined in a single explore.
Yes, at least in the top used explores that I looked at :)
Hide unnecessary explores used for populating suggestions, or one-off explores created to power specific dashboards or looks.
There are some explores called "Test". If you need to keep explores for developer reasons, you can use the hidden parameter on the explore.

A model is a customized portal into the database, designed to provide intuitive data exploration for specific business users. Multiple models can exist for the same database connection in a single LookML project.
Within a project, multiple Models are used for managing data access.
It seems that models are more so used to organize different types of data/ use cases (news sites vs continued education).
You can use models to control user permissions, and this will probably be important when you let the sales team (and other business user teams) into Looker.
To block off certain users from certain explores:
1. Think about the different types of data access (ex: sales, customer success, engineering might all get different types of data access)
2. Separate the data for these different people into different model files
3. Create a model set for each model (https://docs.looker.com/admin-options/settings/roles#model_sets)

4. Create a role, which is a combination of permission set + model set. For example, maybe within the sales team, you have a role for sales explorer (exploring permission set + sales model set) and sales viewer (view-only permission set + sales model set)

*It's also common that there aren't a lot of data restrictions needed across teams. In that case, it's fine to use the "all models" model set for your roles. If you ever import a data set that is restricted to some users, you would need to go back and change all the people with "all models" access to only accessing the non-private models. Therefore, it's better in the beginning to create a model set called "non private models", and put all the models in it, so in the future if you upload a private mode, it's simple to make a new model set which only the high security people have access to.
Avoid using wildcards with include statements ( *.views.lkml, *.dashboards.lkml) to improve LookML validation performance.
This will be easier once you have folders set up.
Right now, this model includes all view files: https://haymarket.looker.com/projects/haymarket/files/hmi_ga.model.lkml
Which is unnecessary because it only has explores for a subset of view files.
The cost is that the LookML validator takes longer to validate your LookML code because it has to scan more files for dependencies.
Model files should not consist of any view declarations. Only explore, datagroup, named_value_format and map_layer declarations should be added to Model files.
A project is a collection of LookML files that describe how your database tables are related to each other and how Looker should interpret those tables.
Separate Projects are used when there are silo'd application teams or development groups with limited need for collaboration between teams.
Separate Projects are used when teams have different deployment schedules/release cycles.
It sounds like you have one team of developers, so one project is dandy!

A slow user experience is frustrating and makes adoption difficult, but delivering instant answers to your users is magical. The cumulative effects of computing horsepower, clever summarization in the model, judicious use of caching, appropriate configuration, and simplified content make magic possible.
The System Activity > Performance Audit dashboard is used regularly to check for errors, optimize data delivery schedules, and identify slow content
datagroup_trigger aligns PDT generation with data pipeline to coordinate refreshing of dashboards, looks, and scheduled data deliveries to ETL processes
this is used lightly - should be used in more derived tables.

In general, more tables should be persisted to the scratch schema (see separate doc about this), and when they are, they should use datagroup_triggers instead of more uniform triggers (like "persist_for")
Any PDTs with generation times greater than one hour have been moved out of Looker and into the data pipeline

Be aware of this! As you persist more derived tables, monitor how long they take to build. One limitation of bigquery is that you cannot create materialized views from queries referencing multiple tables. So you would need to move any of these queries into an ETL cycle before they get to Looker.
Dashboards with multiple single-value visualizations use the fewest number of looks possible to fetch visualization values, by selectively hiding fields
I didn't check your dashboards to see if this was the case, but be aware! This is a nifty way of having the same 1 query power multiple single-value KPIs.
Instant dashboards are turned off in favour of root-cause performance optimization
Yes. You can monitor this under Admin > Instance Performance on the tile "Dashboard with Auto-Refresh On"

You can even explore from here on that tile, and set up an alert that notifies you if this query ever returns results! That way, you can be proactively notified if someone ever sets up auto-refresh, and bother them to make sure they had a good reason for doing so. :)

Looker has a complex security model that allows you to fine-tune content access, data access, and feature access to an almost infinite degree. Following best practices to configure end-user access and permissions ensures the security model remains robust, flexible, and most of all, understandable.
Build a foundation to rely on by making sure every database that Looker connects to is configured properly. Looker works best with massively parallel processing (MPP) database architectures.
